WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:04.730
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:23.140 --> 00:00:25.620
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum:
Good evening, everyone.

00:00:25.620 --> 00:00:27.570
Welcome. Glad you can make it.

00:00:27.570 --> 00:00:28.870
My name is Larry Appelbaum.

00:00:28.870 --> 00:00:30.880
I'm one of the music
specialists here

00:00:30.880 --> 00:00:33.460
in the Music Division
of the Library.

00:00:33.460 --> 00:00:36.700
I think everyone is gathered
here tonight in anticipation

00:00:36.700 --> 00:00:40.060
with this concert we're
about to hear.

00:00:40.060 --> 00:00:44.180
And it is with great pleasure that
I'm going to take a few minutes

00:00:44.180 --> 00:00:47.110
to talk with the composer,
the arranger,

00:00:47.110 --> 00:00:50.750
and the band leader,
Maria Schneider.

00:00:50.750 --> 00:00:52.550
Please help me welcome her.

00:00:52.550 --> 00:01:01.070
[ Applause ]

00:01:01.070 --> 00:01:04.660
So here we are and we're about
90 minutes before show time.

00:01:04.660 --> 00:01:06.070
What kind of things
go through your mind?

00:01:06.070 --> 00:01:08.570
Do you have like a
checklist of things

00:01:08.570 --> 00:01:10.820
that you have to do before concert?

00:01:10.820 --> 00:01:12.120
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider:
Well, it depends,

00:01:12.120 --> 00:01:14.380
like tonight we're playing a
piece called "Cerulean Skies"

00:01:14.380 --> 00:01:17.640
that has bird calls and
I don't have my people

00:01:17.640 --> 00:01:19.610
from the audience that participate.

00:01:19.610 --> 00:01:21.500
There is supposed to be
birds around the room.

00:01:21.500 --> 00:01:22.800
So, I'm like, OK.

00:01:22.800 --> 00:01:25.810
Somebody said we have to
hermetically seal the bird calls

00:01:25.810 --> 00:01:28.010
or putting tape around them so
that people don't get germs.

00:01:28.010 --> 00:01:29.400
[ Laughter ]

00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:32.570
You know, those kind of-- There's
a lot of logistical things.

00:01:32.570 --> 00:01:34.820
And then there is talking
to somebody in the band

00:01:34.820 --> 00:01:37.760
because we're doing a premiere,
you know, so talking about, "Hey,

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:42.020
when you do that line,
can you try this?"

00:01:42.020 --> 00:01:45.070
You know, just always a few
little last minute details.

00:01:45.070 --> 00:01:47.110
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Speaking
of this premier tonight,

00:01:47.110 --> 00:01:51.620
Maria has been commissioned
to write a new work

00:01:51.620 --> 00:01:54.250
and you will be the first
audience to hear it.

00:01:54.250 --> 00:01:58.150
Why don't you tell us a
little about the piece itself,

00:01:58.150 --> 00:02:03.120
what context it comes out of, and
maybe something about the music?

00:02:03.120 --> 00:02:04.420
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: OK.

00:02:04.420 --> 00:02:06.370 position:56%
So, whenever I get a commission, I--

00:02:06.370 --> 00:02:09.880
I don't know, I almost
panic a little bit,

00:02:09.880 --> 00:02:13.570
feel a lot of pressure,
you know, torture.

00:02:13.570 --> 00:02:17.190
And I started working
on this and writing

00:02:17.190 --> 00:02:19.340
and there were a few
things that came to me.

00:02:19.340 --> 00:02:23.200
One was that as I was
working on it, the--

00:02:23.200 --> 00:02:26.170
it was a little bit of a different
sound and a different approach

00:02:26.170 --> 00:02:28.450
and a different something that--

00:02:28.450 --> 00:02:31.220
than what I had before and
I immediately recognized

00:02:31.220 --> 00:02:35.160
that it was the influence of having
worked with David Bowie a year

00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:41.150 position:56%
and a half before and the project
that we did and the kind of attitude

00:02:41.150 --> 00:02:46.900
and the sense of freedom
and fun and risk-taking

00:02:46.900 --> 00:02:50.460
that he made me feel
very comfortable doing

00:02:50.460 --> 00:02:52.530
and kind of that he reveled in.

00:02:52.530 --> 00:02:55.380
So, it's got some of that
and it's got the intensity.

00:02:55.380 --> 00:02:57.580
He really liked my
intense dark music.

00:02:57.580 --> 00:03:03.030
And it kind of made me
explore that dark side.

00:03:03.030 --> 00:03:05.800
But then as I as writing
it, also at the same time,

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:08.620
many of you maybe know or if
you don't know, I will tell you,

00:03:08.620 --> 00:03:15.020
I'm quite into the whole thing
of what is happening right now

00:03:15.020 --> 00:03:19.370
in our digital world and
rights for music creators

00:03:19.370 --> 00:03:21.690
and creators of all kinds.

00:03:21.690 --> 00:03:26.870
But specifically my interest from
my perspective is music creation

00:03:26.870 --> 00:03:31.330
and this idea that there are
these companies that are sort

00:03:31.330 --> 00:03:35.250
of seducing us with the
idea of seducing musicians

00:03:35.250 --> 00:03:39.220
that exposure is wonderful,
seducing everybody that, you know,

00:03:39.220 --> 00:03:47.090 position:56%
more is better and this concept that
free is just the way it has to be.

00:03:47.090 --> 00:03:51.510
But it's very conveniently-- it's
very convenient that the people

00:03:51.510 --> 00:03:55.430 position:56%
that are making it free are actually
becoming very, very rich off of it.

00:03:55.430 --> 00:04:00.940
There's a massive redistribution
of wealth to these small companies

00:04:00.940 --> 00:04:04.450
that are becoming huge and
they are big data companies.

00:04:04.450 --> 00:04:08.050
And, you know, we're talking
like Alphabet, Google, YouTube

00:04:08.050 --> 00:04:13.490
and this kind on inducement of
infringement to gather this data.

00:04:13.490 --> 00:04:15.930
And this data is making
these companies

00:04:15.930 --> 00:04:17.910
like Google more and more powerful.

00:04:17.910 --> 00:04:21.350 position:56%
And there are people and
scientists and people that speculate

00:04:21.350 --> 00:04:27.100
that by the year 2035, artificial
intelligence could become more

00:04:27.100 --> 00:04:28.490
intelligent than we are.

00:04:28.490 --> 00:04:31.120
And actually, that
could be catastrophic.

00:04:31.120 --> 00:04:34.100
You know, some say utopian,
some say catastrophic

00:04:34.100 --> 00:04:35.960
and it could go different
directions.

00:04:35.960 --> 00:04:38.470
For-- I can tell you for the
music industry right now, it--

00:04:38.470 --> 00:04:41.430
or not the industry,
the music makers,

00:04:41.430 --> 00:04:45.580 position:56%
the people that make the music
because you have the music industry,

00:04:45.580 --> 00:04:48.600
you have the internet, big data--

00:04:48.600 --> 00:04:51.650
and the piece I wrote
is called "Data Lords".

00:04:51.650 --> 00:04:54.860
So the data lords, but
what they're resting on

00:04:54.860 --> 00:04:56.630
and how they're attracting people

00:04:56.630 --> 00:05:00.930
to amass all these data
is on the music creator.

00:05:00.930 --> 00:05:03.080
You know, that's the
attractor, make that free

00:05:03.080 --> 00:05:05.800
and then you get all these eyeballs
and then you get the information

00:05:05.800 --> 00:05:07.100
of how people move around.

00:05:07.100 --> 00:05:12.570 position:56%
So, the piece is about the seduction
and then this gathering of data.

00:05:12.570 --> 00:05:15.860
So there's this intensity that
comes through and it just kind

00:05:15.860 --> 00:05:18.010
of overtakes us at the end.

00:05:18.010 --> 00:05:19.430
[ Laughter ]

00:05:19.430 --> 00:05:20.730
We'll see.

00:05:20.730 --> 00:05:22.030
So, "Data Lords", yeah.

00:05:22.030 --> 00:05:24.120
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum:
"Data Lords", yeah.

00:05:24.120 --> 00:05:26.440
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: So, and also,
as I was writing, I thought, well,

00:05:26.440 --> 00:05:27.740
this is perfect, you know?

00:05:27.740 --> 00:05:29.360
I'm going to Library
of Congress, you know?

00:05:29.360 --> 00:05:30.660
Oh, there's a copyright, you know?

00:05:30.660 --> 00:05:35.350
It's like OK, Washington D.C., this
is a good place to unleash my--

00:05:35.350 --> 00:05:37.010
the holy hell of the data lords.

00:05:37.010 --> 00:05:38.310
[ Laughter ]

00:05:38.310 --> 00:05:40.500 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: It's interesting
to hear you talk about that,

00:05:40.500 --> 00:05:48.500
because I want to know what
choices a creative artist has today

00:05:48.500 --> 00:05:50.500
when faced with these things.

00:05:50.500 --> 00:05:55.240
I mean, you talk about the
seduction of promotion,

00:05:55.240 --> 00:05:57.360
for example, or exposure.

00:05:57.360 --> 00:05:59.910
Well, of course, when people
are starting out, they need--

00:05:59.910 --> 00:06:01.300
in fact, they feel
they must have that.

00:06:01.300 --> 00:06:06.770
But what real choices do people
have other than to be co-opted?

00:06:06.770 --> 00:06:10.470
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider:
The-- For me, I'm--

00:06:10.470 --> 00:06:13.790
I would say that I'm one of the
few musicians that has managed

00:06:13.790 --> 00:06:17.230
in this climate of what's going on,

00:06:17.230 --> 00:06:23.520
and I became very inoculated
before it really hit luckily

00:06:23.520 --> 00:06:26.560
because a friend of mine started
this company called ArtistShare.

00:06:26.560 --> 00:06:29.900
And the whole idea is that the
artist owns their own work,

00:06:29.900 --> 00:06:33.580
the artist sells directly to
the fan through the internet

00:06:33.580 --> 00:06:36.880
and through ArtistShare that
they share all the data.

00:06:36.880 --> 00:06:39.800
So when somebody buys my music or--

00:06:39.800 --> 00:06:44.320
you know, through my
site, I know who they are.

00:06:44.320 --> 00:06:48.500
It's not some other company using
that data but it's my information.

00:06:48.500 --> 00:06:52.620
And the idea is that I
am not just sharing music

00:06:52.620 --> 00:06:55.170
but I'm sharing the
whole creative process.

00:06:55.170 --> 00:06:56.550
So whenever I do a project,

00:06:56.550 --> 00:06:58.640
I announce I'm going
to be doing a project.

00:06:58.640 --> 00:07:01.570
I don't have to start
from square one each time

00:07:01.570 --> 00:07:05.610 position:56%
because I have amass this fan base
now, because I've been doing project

00:07:05.610 --> 00:07:09.210
after project, commissions
and recordings, and recordings

00:07:09.210 --> 00:07:13.990
that are $200,000, and
managing to pay for them

00:07:13.990 --> 00:07:18.110
because of this relationship
that I've made.

00:07:18.110 --> 00:07:22.480
So, for me and what I tell all
musicians now is self-ownership is

00:07:22.480 --> 00:07:27.340
king, having your own
relationship with those people

00:07:27.340 --> 00:07:31.400
that you establish, that
relationship of trust and respect,

00:07:31.400 --> 00:07:34.820
giving them things that are fun.

00:07:34.820 --> 00:07:40.390
So they feel like, you know, wow,
this is so much more special than,

00:07:40.390 --> 00:07:44.000
you know, just going and
streaming something somewhere.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:46.710
Wow, I'm getting this
whole inside story.

00:07:46.710 --> 00:07:48.010
And it's fun for me.

00:07:48.010 --> 00:07:53.220
The connection is beautiful
because it's-- Yeah, so it's that.

00:07:53.220 --> 00:07:55.890
And then the other thing is there
is a group of us in New York

00:07:55.890 --> 00:08:01.240
that have started, you know, a
campaign called Musicanswers.org.

00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:03.380
And one thing that's
happening in this--

00:08:03.380 --> 00:08:07.200
in the music industry and even
with people that, you know, lobby,

00:08:07.200 --> 00:08:12.600
Congress and everything, is that
some of the music organizations

00:08:12.600 --> 00:08:15.000
that are doing it, they
are doing wonderful work

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:16.630
but there is a little
bit of a problem

00:08:16.630 --> 00:08:19.750
and that sometimes the record
companies and the publishers are

00:08:19.750 --> 00:08:23.120
in those organizations with
the people that make the music.

00:08:23.120 --> 00:08:25.800
And some of those record companies

00:08:25.800 --> 00:08:29.020
and publishers have actually
joined the data lords.

00:08:29.020 --> 00:08:32.630
You know, Sony, Universal,
Warner all took equity--

00:08:32.630 --> 00:08:35.300 position:56%
and Spotify, Spotify is a data lord.

00:08:35.300 --> 00:08:39.050
You know, they're making music free
to attract eyeballs to amass data

00:08:39.050 --> 00:08:43.240
and sell advertising and
with a lack of transparency.

00:08:43.240 --> 00:08:47.840
So the idea that we had
was to start this campaign

00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:51.540
where we educate musicians and
people, any-- all of you can join.

00:08:51.540 --> 00:08:54.460
You can go and sign up and just
say, "I'm a fan of the music,

00:08:54.460 --> 00:08:58.810
I'm in the music industry," or
"I'm a composer, a songwriter,

00:08:58.810 --> 00:09:03.550
a producer or performer."

00:09:03.550 --> 00:09:06.180
That's who we're advocating for.

00:09:06.180 --> 00:09:08.730
So we have videos up about YouTube.

00:09:08.730 --> 00:09:11.440
We're going to have things
you should always have

00:09:11.440 --> 00:09:14.190
in a publishing contract,
language you should never have

00:09:14.190 --> 00:09:18.010
in a publishing contract, the
idea of empowering musicians

00:09:18.010 --> 00:09:24.330
because we have been sitting ducks
for so long because, first of all,

00:09:24.330 --> 00:09:29.290
we love what we do and what we most
want is that you love what we do.

00:09:29.290 --> 00:09:34.790
So, if you-- if many musicians
will just give it away just

00:09:34.790 --> 00:09:39.120
to be appreciated, and of course,
you know, industry looks at this

00:09:39.120 --> 00:09:41.560
and say, "What a bunch
of idiots," you know?

00:09:41.560 --> 00:09:48.720
And to some extent, musicians
and artists, there was a history

00:09:48.720 --> 00:09:54.580
of feeling like you're-- that
if you are the starving artist,

00:09:54.580 --> 00:09:58.660
there is something-- that's
an incredible story, you know?

00:09:58.660 --> 00:10:01.630
So it's like, wow, they
actually feel more special

00:10:01.630 --> 00:10:04.010
when they're a starving
artist, excellent, you know?

00:10:04.010 --> 00:10:05.310
[ Laughter ]

00:10:05.310 --> 00:10:08.570
You know, let's use them up
and suck them dry, you know?

00:10:08.570 --> 00:10:13.940
So this is-- So to me, it's
education and it's very difficult

00:10:13.940 --> 00:10:17.270
to move Congress and, you
know, the Subcommittee

00:10:17.270 --> 00:10:20.360
on Intellectual Property
is very difficult to move

00:10:20.360 --> 00:10:23.670
that when you've got buildings of
lobbyists from Google and YouTube

00:10:23.670 --> 00:10:27.500
and this revolving door between
government and these companies.

00:10:27.500 --> 00:10:31.880
But, if the-- if you have the
power of this list of names--

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:34.220
and we have Carole King,
we have Herbie Hancock,

00:10:34.220 --> 00:10:37.440
we have so many people now, you
know, just a lot of musicians

00:10:37.440 --> 00:10:38.750
and students and everybody.

00:10:38.750 --> 00:10:41.880
And if we're all getting
this knowledge

00:10:41.880 --> 00:10:44.340
and we're saying we are
watching you and we do not

00:10:44.340 --> 00:10:48.060
like what you're doing,
suddenly there's a shame factor.

00:10:48.060 --> 00:10:51.830
And so sometimes, I think that the
strongest change you can make is

00:10:51.830 --> 00:10:53.500
that, you know?

00:10:53.500 --> 00:10:58.110
And then everything has to change,
you know, rather than mandating it

00:10:58.110 --> 00:10:59.710
through law, but yes,
I would like the law

00:10:59.710 --> 00:11:03.580
to change regarding
the digital rights

00:11:03.580 --> 00:11:06.950
and Safe Harbor Rules
and all these things.

00:11:06.950 --> 00:11:10.140
But, you know, you have
to be reasonable, too,

00:11:10.140 --> 00:11:12.110
and we don't know what can change.

00:11:12.110 --> 00:11:16.620
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Every time
I hear you speak about this

00:11:16.620 --> 00:11:22.080
and others, I wonder who
really owns the music.

00:11:22.080 --> 00:11:25.360
We often prefer to believe
that the creators do,

00:11:25.360 --> 00:11:32.470
the people who actually dream up
or even manufacturer or record

00:11:32.470 --> 00:11:36.580
or whatever it might be,
that creative process.

00:11:36.580 --> 00:11:39.060
But who really does own the music?

00:11:39.060 --> 00:11:40.470
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider:
Well, I guess it--

00:11:40.470 --> 00:11:44.960
I mean to me, the person
that creates the music,

00:11:44.960 --> 00:11:48.130
the copyright holder, the
person who makes the music.

00:11:48.130 --> 00:11:50.580
I mean if you-- there
is that other level too

00:11:50.580 --> 00:11:53.100
that you can copyright a recording.

00:11:53.100 --> 00:11:56.000
But, you know, the
thing that people forget

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.230
and I think what's
happened is as we've gotten

00:11:58.230 --> 00:12:02.040
from the physical product-- and a
guy, Marshall Gilkes, in my band,

00:12:02.040 --> 00:12:03.990
he just did a panel about this.

00:12:03.990 --> 00:12:07.750
And he came up with an incredible
point that I hadn't thought about.

00:12:07.750 --> 00:12:10.730
He said, "You know, it
wasn't that long ago

00:12:10.730 --> 00:12:12.800
when Tower Records said
they would wrap those CDs

00:12:12.800 --> 00:12:15.740
in those plastic things that
would beep when you would go out

00:12:15.740 --> 00:12:19.150
and the cop would arrest you
if you stole that, you know?"

00:12:19.150 --> 00:12:21.090
So what is the difference
between that

00:12:21.090 --> 00:12:23.840
and grabbing the file somewhere?

00:12:23.840 --> 00:12:29.950
So, you know, I think people have
come to think that if music is

00:12:29.950 --> 00:12:32.220
out there, that sort of
ephemeral, beautiful thing,

00:12:32.220 --> 00:12:34.860
it's all of ours, it's
so easy to access.

00:12:34.860 --> 00:12:37.090
But it is an asset.

00:12:37.090 --> 00:12:40.120
You know, when you write
that music, the investment.

00:12:40.120 --> 00:12:43.010
When I made my last
recording, "Thompson Fields",

00:12:43.010 --> 00:12:45.910
it's a $200,000 recording.

00:12:45.910 --> 00:12:50.290
Just recording it, you know,
the planning of it, the mixing--

00:12:50.290 --> 00:12:53.050
the editing, the mixing,
the mastering,

00:12:53.050 --> 00:12:55.900
the putting the book
together, it was a full year

00:12:55.900 --> 00:12:59.350
where I couldn't really work
and make money that much

00:12:59.350 --> 00:13:01.140
because I was doing that.

00:13:01.140 --> 00:13:04.830
So that $200,000 doesn't
include that I wasn't paid.

00:13:04.830 --> 00:13:07.580
Now, we haven't talked
about the years proceeding

00:13:07.580 --> 00:13:09.470
up to it writing all the music.

00:13:09.470 --> 00:13:12.670
So we're talking like
a $400,000 investment.

00:13:12.670 --> 00:13:13.970
That's an asset.

00:13:13.970 --> 00:13:16.010
That's my 401(k), right?

00:13:16.010 --> 00:13:17.310
[ Laughter ]

00:13:17.310 --> 00:13:19.460
So this is like-- you
know, I remember Congress.

00:13:19.460 --> 00:13:22.130
I just-- I wanted to look at
them and just say, just imagine--

00:13:22.130 --> 00:13:24.750
because I got to testify
before the Subcommittee

00:13:24.750 --> 00:13:26.050
on Intellectual Property.

00:13:26.050 --> 00:13:30.400 position:56%
And I didn't get the chance to say
it, but I wanted to say, imagine if,

00:13:30.400 --> 00:13:33.880
you know, we build some kind of
app that could go on to your 401(k)

00:13:33.880 --> 00:13:36.170
that was just like, oh
wow, this is so cool.

00:13:36.170 --> 00:13:39.240 position:56%
People can just take little snippets
off from Farenthold and this

00:13:39.240 --> 00:13:41.070
and that, you know, just
grab Chaffetz, you know,

00:13:41.070 --> 00:13:43.290
like he's got a lot of money,
let's take some of that, you know,

00:13:43.290 --> 00:13:44.990
oh yeah, share, free for all.

00:13:44.990 --> 00:13:46.960
Isn't this fun, isn't this great?

00:13:46.960 --> 00:13:49.870
But then add to it that
the people that are doing

00:13:49.870 --> 00:13:53.480
that aren't just taking the money,
they're actually becoming rich

00:13:53.480 --> 00:13:57.200
from it because they're gathering
the information from this thing.

00:13:57.200 --> 00:13:58.680
I mean, it's incredible.

