00:38:13.090 --> 00:38:15.490
Even when I write, I don't
say, OK, I'm going to write

00:38:15.490 --> 00:38:16.790
for the Library of Congress.

00:38:16.790 --> 00:38:19.270
I want to do something
about you know big data.

00:38:19.270 --> 00:38:20.980
You know, it's never like that.

00:38:20.980 --> 00:38:25.050
It's sort of-- In a way,
well, I am glad I've done

00:38:25.050 --> 00:38:27.360
that because I would have
never imagined really--

00:38:27.360 --> 00:38:30.250
I mean, I did try to call Gil
Evans but I didn't meet him

00:38:30.250 --> 00:38:31.970
because I tried to call him.

00:38:31.970 --> 00:38:33.400
I would have never
thought of working

00:38:33.400 --> 00:38:35.080
with David Bowie in
a thousand years.

00:38:35.080 --> 00:38:38.180
And I had that just a
little bit space in my life

00:38:38.180 --> 00:38:39.970
that allowed that to come.

00:38:39.970 --> 00:38:43.230
But that being said, there is one
thing I dream of doing that's going

00:38:43.230 --> 00:38:45.840
to surprise-- I don't know
if we talked about this.

00:38:45.840 --> 00:38:47.630
It's a crazy thing.

00:38:47.630 --> 00:38:51.380
But it involves finding
the right collaborator.

00:38:51.380 --> 00:38:54.060
Someday I want to write a show.

00:38:54.060 --> 00:38:55.810
Isn't that crazy?

00:38:55.810 --> 00:39:00.860
But I do. And you know what did
it to me, I saw light on a piazza.

00:39:00.860 --> 00:39:03.070
Did any of you see that production?

00:39:03.070 --> 00:39:04.850
Raise your hand if you saw it.

00:39:04.850 --> 00:39:07.160
I was so moved and
it was so beautiful.

00:39:07.160 --> 00:39:10.300
And I just said, "Yeah,
I want to write a show."

00:39:10.300 --> 00:39:13.680
Because I wrote songs
for Dawn Upshaw,

00:39:13.680 --> 00:39:16.960
and the experience
of writing for words.

00:39:16.960 --> 00:39:19.100
At first I was scared
because I thought, oh my God.

00:39:19.100 --> 00:39:21.650
You know, it's already hard
enough just to write notes.

00:39:21.650 --> 00:39:24.080
Now, I got to figure out I
wasn't writing the words.

00:39:24.080 --> 00:39:27.540 position:56%
I was using the poetry of Ted Cruz
but now I got figure out how to make

00:39:27.540 --> 00:39:30.690
that fit in the context and all of
this, and there's another layer.

00:39:30.690 --> 00:39:32.140
But it wasn't like that.

00:39:32.140 --> 00:39:36.010
It was liberating because I love
the words and I love the sentiment.

00:39:36.010 --> 00:39:41.560
And then that gave me the
impetus to-- it led me.

00:39:41.560 --> 00:39:42.860
It led me.

00:39:42.860 --> 00:39:47.790
Instead of me always having to
go into this blank space of any--

00:39:47.790 --> 00:39:52.450
of infinity, suddenly there's this
little beacon that says here I am.

00:39:52.450 --> 00:39:55.600
I nurture-- you know, make me,

00:39:55.600 --> 00:39:57.780
make me come alive and
sound or something.

00:39:57.780 --> 00:40:01.150
So, if I could find the right
story, the right collaborator,

00:40:01.150 --> 00:40:02.450
that would be a dream of mine.

00:40:02.450 --> 00:40:04.320
That's like the only-- otherwise,

00:40:04.320 --> 00:40:07.490
I just want to keep developing
the sound with the band

00:40:07.490 --> 00:40:11.300
and see what comes, you know?

00:40:11.300 --> 00:40:13.090
Improvising life.

00:40:13.090 --> 00:40:16.390
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: I actually
think we have only time

00:40:16.390 --> 00:40:17.690
for one last question.

00:40:17.690 --> 00:40:19.510
And if you don't mind
I'm going to take it.

00:40:19.510 --> 00:40:22.140
[ Laughter ]

00:40:22.140 --> 00:40:27.060
Yes. Is recognition
important to you?

00:40:27.060 --> 00:40:29.370
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: It never
really-- you know what?

00:40:29.370 --> 00:40:32.900
When I started this--
That's really good question.

00:40:32.900 --> 00:40:36.260
When I started out, I never--

00:40:36.260 --> 00:40:40.220
I thought I would be a music
copyist probably forever

00:40:40.220 --> 00:40:42.450 position:56%
and just have my band and, you know.

00:40:42.450 --> 00:40:46.860 position:56%
And I just kind of expected that and
then I thought I could also waitress

00:40:46.860 --> 00:40:49.810
because I stopped waitressing
in Minnesota.

00:40:49.810 --> 00:40:52.310 position:56%
And I was a terrible waitress but I
figured that I could get it together

00:40:52.310 --> 00:40:55.250
to be a New York waitress
if I needed to.

00:40:55.250 --> 00:40:58.770
And so, I never expected
any of this.

00:40:58.770 --> 00:41:03.390
So, I would say it's fun because
it's fun to share my music.

00:41:03.390 --> 00:41:06.360
And yeah, it's really fun
to win a Grammy Award.

00:41:06.360 --> 00:41:08.240
I discovered that.

00:41:08.240 --> 00:41:10.530
And maybe it was because I remember

00:41:10.530 --> 00:41:14.660
when I was kid once giving a Grammy
speech in my living room privately.

00:41:14.660 --> 00:41:15.960
So--

00:41:15.960 --> 00:41:17.260
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum:
Into your hairbrush?

00:41:17.260 --> 00:41:18.560
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yeah,
something like that, you know?

00:41:18.560 --> 00:41:21.770
Just standing up on a stool
and I'd like to think.

00:41:21.770 --> 00:41:26.010
But I did-- I pretended I was
Ms. America once, too, you know?

00:41:26.010 --> 00:41:29.200
So we all did these things.

00:41:29.200 --> 00:41:34.510
But it's-- as a musician it is
really great to be appreciated.

00:41:34.510 --> 00:41:36.310
I will say that, absolutely.

00:41:36.310 --> 00:41:39.710
Did I count on it and
do it for this, no.

00:41:39.710 --> 00:41:42.090
I expected very little, actually.

00:41:42.090 --> 00:41:44.790
So, it's just I've been very lucky.

00:41:44.790 --> 00:41:48.150
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Well, I hope
you can appreciate how many people

00:41:48.150 --> 00:41:50.390
on this room feel that
way about you.

00:41:50.390 --> 00:41:51.690
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Oh, thank you.

00:41:51.690 --> 00:41:52.990
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: So,
thank you all for coming.

00:41:52.990 --> 00:41:55.290
Thank you, Maria.

